der: 2)
FaqQuestion.create!(id: 8, title: 'How does membership in Phi Kappa Tau prepare an individual to be successful later in life?', content: '<p>The leadership experience you receive when in a fraternity is invaluable. Although we do know how to have fun, we also know how to get work done. Time management is crucial to your college career and Phi Kappa Tau can assist you in this. The ability to balance academics, social life, philanthropy, and sleep in order to get the most out of your college experience is the single greatest gift Phi Kappa Tau can give you. However, this is not the only way in which Phi Tau prepares its members. It is no coincidence that so many Phi Taus end up with rewarding jobs; the people you meet and the connections you form make it easier to find better co-ops while in school and better jobs after graduation. In addition, the social skills you develop provide you with the required skills for job interviews and meeting people.</p>', faq_category_id: 3, order: 1)
FaqQuestion.create!(id: 9, title: 'What is meant by "Building Men of Character" or "Honor and Credit"?', content: '<p>Phi Kappa Tau is a values-based organization. We strive to make the most out of our members through the experiences we live. There is a strong focus on character and developing that character during your experience with Phi Kappa Tau. Do you know the six pillars of character? If you answered no, then Phi Tau may be a good place for you. We pride ourselves on a hazing-free new member program. Instead of humiliating our new members, we teach them character. We are building men of character. We strive to bring honor and credit to our organization through the lives we lead.</p>', faq_category_id: 3, order: 2)
FaqQuestion.create!(id: 10, title: 'How does involvement in service projects, social programs and intramurals help an individual?', content: '<p>The feelings that you experience when helping others are indescribable. Knowing that YOU made a difference is a feeling that cannot be achieved any other way. Still skeptical? Ask one of us when we are doing a community service event and come along with us. Or if you want something simpler, ask any one of us to see the Hole in the Wall DVD - watching that is the next best thing to experiencing it first hand. Intramural sports are available every quarter for people interested in athletics. Greek intramurals are a totally different experience because of the bond you have with your teammates and the friendly rivalries we have with other houses.</p>', faq_category_id: 4, order: 1)
FaqQuestion.create!(id: 11, title: 'How does Phi Kappa Tau promote scholarship, and how will it help me when I go looking for a job?', content: '<p>Academics come first in Phi Tau. We have members in just about every major at RIT. For example, if you are an Electrical Engineering major, we have older Electrical Engineering majors that can help you study. They have taken the classes you will take. They have had the professors you will have. They know about co-ops. They know about finals. They know the ins and outs to the 10-week quarter system. We teach each other here and that is priceless. When you apply for a job, being a Phi Tau can work to your advantage. Your social experience has prepared you for your job interview. Your GPA and other academic achievements will be excellent because of our focus on scholarship. You will have been involved in philanthropy and community service, which is a crucial part of job placement. We have Phi Taus involved at RIT that can provide excellent letters of recommendation. And finally, we know lots of people all over the nation - Phi Taus like to hire other Phi Taus!</p>', faq_category_id: 4, order: 2)
FaqQuestion.create!(id: 12, title: 'What are some general facts about members of Greek letter organizations?', content: '<p>Fraternity and Sorority Alumni are much more likely than nonmembers to participate in community service activities after graduation Forty-three of the 100 members of the U.S. Senate are members of a fraternity or sorority 29% of the U.S. House of Representatives are Greek affiliated Of North Americas 50 largest corporations, 43 are headed by Greek men and women 7 out of 10 people listed in "Whos Who?" are Greek 85% of Fortune 500 executives are Greek 40 of 47 U.S. Supreme Court Justices are Greek All but two Presidents and two Vice-Presidents, born after the founding of the first social fraternity in 1825, were fraternity members 63% of all U.S. Cabinet members since 1900 have been Greek All of the Apollo 11 astronauts were Greek Only 2% of the population are members of Greek organizations A U.S. Government study shows that over 70% of Greeks graduate, while under 50% of non-Greeks graduate A study by the University of Missouri found that Greeks throughout the US and Canada are more involved on their campuses and rate their overall university experience better The same Missouri study found Greeks are more financially successful after they graduate than independents, are more involved in their communities, and give more generously to their alma matters Greeks not only participate in their own fraternity or sorority leadership, but are also involved in the same extracurricular activities as non affiliated students As undergraduates, Greeks raise approximately $7 million per year for charities As undergraduates, Greeks give approximately 850,000 volunteer hours per year Greek alumni are more satisfied with the social and cultural aspects of the college experience than non affiliated students Greek affiliation has a significant impact on the current income of alumni Employers consider 18 key factors in evaluating job interviews...the Greek community provides opportunity to develop 12 of those key factors: Real-World Experience, Leadership Qualities, Personal Presentation, Attitude, Communication Skills, Problem Solving, Community Service Orientation, Adaptability-Drive-Initiative, Proven Track Record, Ability to Learn, Preparation for Interviews</p>', faq_category_id: 4, order: 3)